snippet.textDisplay: I've been reading some of the directors cut responses and if y'all are truly of thinking to remove infusion I'd say that's an overall bad move. By doing this you're going to be forcing the community to play more seriously and reducing the overall enjoyability of the game. There isn't a solid way to get exotic weapons either, so that's going to ruin a big aspect of it. Most other mmo RPGs have generalized weapons (melee weapons for the most part in dark souls and then all insane and off the top weapons in borderlands) that just don't fit into the destiny sandbox. The sandbox as is is formulated to how a person plays allowing for people to have preferences. It allows player to say they want to keep a raid weapon they got and really like from 3 years ago or something. In a fps rpg like borderlands all the weapons are useful and the pvp aspect isn't as prominent compared to destiny's. snippet.textOriginal: I've been reading some of the directors cut responses and if y'all are truly of thinking to remove infusion I'd say that's an overall bad move. By doing this you're going to be forcing the community to play more seriously and reducing the overall enjoyability of the game. There isn't a solid way to get exotic weapons either, so that's going to ruin a big aspect of it. Most other mmo RPGs have generalized weapons (melee weapons for the most part in dark souls and then all insane and off the top weapons in borderlands) that just don't fit into the destiny sandbox. The sandbox as is is formulated to how a person plays allowing for people to have preferences. It allows player to say they want to keep a raid weapon they got and really like from 3 years ago or something. In a fps rpg like borderlands all the weapons are useful and the pvp aspect isn't as prominent compared to destiny's. If you want to add meaning to newer weapons increase the cost of infusion, don't remove it completely
